  "aboutCaesarTitle": "About Caesar Cipher algorithm",
  "whatIsCaesarTitle": "📌 What is it",
  "whatIsCaesarContent": "The Caesar Cipher is an extremely simple symmetric encryption algorithm based on substitution.\n\nIt works by shifting each letter of the alphabet by a fixed number of positions.\n\nExample (shift of 3):\nA → D\nB → E\nC → F\n...",
  "originCaesarTitle": "🏛️ Historical Origin",
  "originCaesarContent": "The cipher is named after Julius Caesar, who used it to protect military communications during the Roman Republic period (around 50 BC).\n\nHe used a fixed shift of 3 letters to send messages to his generals.",
  "howItWorksCaesarTitle": "⚙️ How it works (conceptually)",
  "howItWorksCaesarContent": "• An integer called the shift value (k) is defined\n• For each letter:\n  - Locate its position in the alphabet\n  - Add the shift value\n  - Apply modulo 26 (to \"wrap around\" the alphabet)",
  "characteristicsCaesarTitle": "🧠 Technical Characteristics",
  "characteristicsCaesarContent": "• Type: Symmetric encryption\n• Complexity: Very low\n• Security: Practically non-existent\n• Key space: Only 25 possibilities",
  "usageHistoryCaesarTitle": "⚔️ Usage throughout History",
  "usageHistoryCaesarContent": "• Military communication in Ancient Rome\n• Conceptual basis for classical cryptography\n• Widely used in introductory security teaching",
  "limitationsCaesarTitle": "🚨 Limitations",
  "limitationsCaesarContent": "• Vulnerable to frequency analysis\n• Can be broken by brute force in seconds\n• Does not offer real confidentiality today",
  "currentUsageCaesarTitle": "📱 Current Usage",
  "currentUsageCaesarContent": "• Teaching cryptography\n• Games and puzzles\n• Demonstration of basic concepts",

  "aboutDiffieHellmanTitle": "About Diffie-Hellman algorithm",
  "whatIsDiffieHellmanTitle": "📌 What is it",
  "whatIsDiffieHellmanContent": "The Diffie-Hellman algorithm is a method for secure cryptographic key exchange.\n\nIt allows two parties to create a shared secret key without ever transmitting it directly.",
  "originDiffieHellmanTitle": "🏛️ Historical Origin",
  "originDiffieHellmanContent": "Proposed in 1976 by:\n• Whitfield Diffie\n• Martin Hellman\n\nIt was the first practical method of public-key cryptography.",
  "ideaDiffieHellmanTitle": "💡 Central Idea",
  "ideaDiffieHellmanContent": "Solving the problem:\n\"How can two people share a secret without ever having communicated securely before?\"",
  "howItWorksDiffieHellmanTitle": "⚙️ How it works (conceptually)",
  "howItWorksDiffieHellmanContent": "1. Both parties publicly agree on:\n   - A large prime number (p)\n   - A generator (g)\n2. Each side chooses a private secret:\n   - A chooses a\n   - B chooses b\n3. Calculate public values:",
  "step45DiffieHellmanContent": "4. Exchange A and B\n5. Calculate shared key:",
  "mathConceptDiffieHellmanTitle": "🧠 Mathematical Concept",
  "mathConceptDiffieHellmanContent": "Based on the discrete logarithm problem.\n\nThis problem is computationally hard to solve, ensuring security.",
  "characteristicsDiffieHellmanTitle": "🛡️ Technical Characteristics",
  "characteristicsDiffieHellmanContent": "• Type: Public-key cryptography\n• Goal: Key exchange, not direct encryption\n• Security: High (with correct parameters)\n• Base: Modular mathematics",
  "usageHistoryDiffieHellmanTitle": "🌐 Usage throughout History",
  "usageHistoryDiffieHellmanContent": "Basis for modern protocols like:\n• TLS/HTTPS\n• VPNs\n• SSH",
  "currentUsageDiffieHellmanTitle": "📱 Current Usage",
  "currentUsageDiffieHellmanContent": "• Establishing secure connections on the internet\n• Banking applications\n• Encrypted communication",
  "limitationsDiffieHellmanTitle": "🚨 Limitations",
  "limitationsDiffieHellmanContent": "• Vulnerable to Man-in-the-Middle attacks if not authenticated\n• Requires use with digital certificates",

  "aboutHashTitle": "About Hash algorithm",
  "whatIsHashTitle": "📌 What is it",
  "whatIsHashContent": "A hash function transforms input data of arbitrary size into an output of fixed size.",
  "originHashTitle": "🏛️ Historical Origin",
  "originHashContent": "The concept emerged within computing, especially in data structures in the 1950s–1970s.\n\nWith the advancement of cryptography, modern cryptographic hash functions emerged such as:\n• MD5\n• SHA-1\n• SHA-256",
  "howItWorksHashTitle": "⚙️ How it works (conceptually)",
  "howItWorksHashContent": "• Receives any input\n• Applies a series of mathematical transformations\n• Produces a fixed value (hash)",
  "importantPropertiesHashTitle": "🧠 Important Properties",
  "importantPropertiesHashContent": "A good hash function must have:\n\n• Determinism: Same input → same output\n• Speed: Efficient computation\n• Avalanche effect: Small change → completely different output\n• Collision resistance: Difficult to find two inputs with the same hash",
  "characteristicsHashTitle": "🛡️ Technical Characteristics",
  "characteristicsHashContent": "• Type: One-way function\n• Non-reversible\n• Used for integrity and verification",
  "usageHistoryHashTitle": "🌐 Usage throughout History",
  "usageHistoryHashContent": "• Data structures (HashMap, HashTable)\n• Secure password storage\n• Digital signatures",
  "currentUsageHashTitle": "📱 Current Usage",
  "currentUsageHashContent": "• User authentication\n• Blockchain\n• File integrity verification\n• Distributed systems",
  "limitationsHashTitle": "🚨 Limitations",
  "limitationsHashContent": "• Collisions are possible (depending on the algorithm)\n• Old algorithms (MD5, SHA-1) are considered insecure",
  "importantObservationHashTitle": "⚠️ Important Observation (architectural)",
  "importantObservationHashContent": "Hash ≠ reversible encryption\n\n• Encryption → can be reversed with a key\n• Hash → cannot be reversed (ideally)",
